spondence, periodicals, and archives to the popular works of H. Rider Haggard, Richard Marsh, and Joseph Conrad. These texts trouble the notions of bounded male bodies, impermeable histories, and solid virtues while underscoring the grotesqueness of male forms, narratives, and moralities. Although dominant representations of martial bodies frequently emphasized boundaries, containment, and solidity, the fiction and imperial archives explored in this book expose problems of stability through tropes, images, and material evidence of perforation, penetration, and dissolution. In emphasizing the relationship between institutional imperial writing and popular discourse, Penetrating Critiques reveals that more complex, fraught, and critical approaches to imperialism and masculinity were circulating throughout Victorian culture than previously recognized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aMasculinity in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aH. Rider Haggard.  aHeart of Darkness.  aJoseph Conrad.  aRichard Marsh.  aVictorian literature.  aadventure writing.  aarchival.  aempire.  afin-de-siècle literature.  agender.  amasculinity.  amilitary.  apopular fiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751341240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487513412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487513412.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles